title: Reality TV: No callback for 'Top Model'
text:
“America’s Next Top Model,” one of the longest-running shows in primetime, will not return after the current season, its 22nd, it was announced last week.
The series first aired in 2003, predating even “The Apprentice” and “Dancing with the Stars.” Through it all, Tyra Banks has been the host and lead judge of the series, which invites a group of young models to compete for a contract with a top agency.
Although the show has yet to produce anyone who might realistically be considered a top model, several of its winners have gone on to minor successes in the entertainment field.
The winner of the first “cycle,” as the show prefers to call its seasons, was Adrianne Curry, who married former “Brady Bunch” kid Christopher Knight and starred with him in “My Fair Brady. Cycle 3 winner Eva Pigford took on the stage name of Eva Marcille and has found regular work as an actor.
The highest-rated show on the CW as recently as 2010, “ANTM” has seen its ratings slide sharply of late. A recent episode drew just 1 million live viewers. The series finale is slated for Dec. 4.
“America’s Next Top Model” airs at 8 p.m. Friday on the CW.
“The Voice” 8 tonight and 9 p.m. Tuesday, NBC It's the battle rounds over the next two nights, with the knockouts beginning next week. Last week’s episodes provided some surprises. Manny Cabo and Krista Hughes, both of whom got all four judges to turn around in their blind auditions, lost their battles and were not stolen.
“Survivor: Cambodia – Second Chances” 8 p.m. Wednesday, CBS Life got a little better for the Angkor tribe last week, as it won a food reward, and then got worse again as the tribe lost its second straight immunity challenge. Jeff Varner, who had first played in 2001 in “The Australian Outback” season, went home.
“Project Runway” 9 p.m. Thursday, Lifetime Kelly Dempsey continued to overturn our expectations by winning her second straight challenge. The contest called for the designers to use a 3D printer to design a piece inspired by New York’s bridges. Less surprising was the elimination of Merline Labissiere, who was good enough to last until late in the contest but never seemed like a real contender.
“The Amazing Race” 8 p.m. Friday, CBS Last week’s episode promised a lot of drama but didn’t deliver much, as everyone passed on U-turning an opponent, and the episode ended with only two teams checked in at the Pit Stop. Friday’s episode will continue in Zimbabwe.
“Dancing With the Stars” 8 tonight, ABC Leah Remini is due to take over as co-host for Erin Andrews in tonight’s episode. Remini will continue in the role for a couple more weeks while Andrews covers postseason baseball for Fox. Remini, who competed on the show in Season 17, sat in for Andrews last year as well.
During last week’s partner switch-up, no couple was eliminated. Scores from that night carriy over to tonight.
